  '426': {
    id: '426', name: 'Lesotho',
    description: 'Basotho cuisine is shaped by the highlands of the Maloti Mountains — maize, sorghum, and legumes are the foundation of a simple but nourishing table. Papa (cornmeal porridge) with moroho (wild spinach) and dried beans is the everyday meal of most Basotho households.',
    keyIngredients: ['cornmeal (papa)', 'sorghum', 'moroho (wild spinach)', 'dried beans', 'pumpkin', 'dried peaches', 'goat', 'soured milk'],
    signatureDishes: [
      { name: 'Papa ne Moroho', description: 'Thick cornmeal porridge served with wild spinach cooked in salt and oil — Lesotho\'s most fundamental everyday meal.' },
      { name: 'Motoho', description: 'Fermented sorghum porridge — a nutritious traditional Basotho breakfast, eaten especially in the mountain villages where sorghum grows at altitude.' },
      { name: 'Braai', description: 'Grilled goat or beef over open charcoal — the shared Southern African barbecue tradition beloved at Lesotho\'s celebrations and soccer events.' },
    ],
    images: [
      { url: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582916400498-fdb6b60b91e0?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4ODU2NjJ8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwxfHxMZXNvdGhvJTIwZm9vZHxlbnwwfHx8fDE3NzI0MTQ2MzJ8MA&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080', alt: '2 men in blue jacket and red helmet standing beside brown cow during daytime' },
      { url: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1653842045754-59b63ea5a58e?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4ODU2NjJ8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwyfHxMZXNvdGhvJTIwZm9vZHxlbnwwfHx8fDE3NzI0MTQ2MzJ8MA&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080', alt: 'a large grassy field with a mountain in the background' },
      { url: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1592600411240-a699d5307f81?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4ODU2NjJ8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwzfHxMZXNvdGhvJTIwZm9vZHxlbnwwfHx8fDE3NzI0MTQ2MzJ8MA&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080', alt: 'woman in blue jacket standing beside brown cow during daytime' }
    ],
    funFact: 'Lesotho is the only country in the world that lies entirely above 1,000 meters in altitude — the world\'s highest country by minimum elevation. The cold, high-altitude climate means Lesotho grows peaches and apricots extraordinarily well; Basotho dried peaches are traded across Southern Africa.',
  },

  '108': {
    id: '108', name: 'Burundi',
    description: 'Burundian cuisine shares many traits with Rwanda — beans, sweet potatoes, and plantains dominate a table shaped by small-farm agriculture on densely populated hills. Ubugali (cornmeal porridge) and isombe (cassava leaf stew) are the daily staples of most Burundian households.',
    keyIngredients: ['beans', 'sweet potatoes', 'cornmeal (ubugali)', 'cassava leaves', 'plantains', 'sorghum beer (urwarwa)', 'peas', 'pumpkin'],
    signatureDishes: [
      { name: 'Ubugali', description: 'Thick cornmeal or cassava porridge — the fundamental starch of Burundi, eaten at every meal with beans or leafy vegetable relish.' },
      { name: 'Isombe', description: 'Pounded cassava leaves cooked with dried fish and palm oil — one of Burundi\'s most beloved and nutritious everyday dishes.' },
      { name: 'Mararamuko', description: 'A bean and banana stew slow-cooked together — a distinctly Burundian combination that reflects the country\'s extraordinary bean diversity.' },
    ],
    images: [
      { url: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1649059370148-616c0aa8e371?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4ODU2NjJ8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwxfHxCdXJ1bmRpJTIwZm9vZHxlbnwwfHx8fDE3NzI0MTQ2MzN8MA&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080', alt: 'a close up of a blender filled with food' }
    ],
    funFact: 'Burundi is Africa\'s largest coffee producer per capita relative to its population — and Burundian specialty coffee is increasingly prized by third-wave coffee roasters worldwide. Burundian farmers grow washed Bourbon arabica at altitude that produces cups with extraordinary fruit complexity.',
  },

  '728': {
    id: '728', name: 'South Sudan',
    description: 'South Sudanese cuisine is one of Africa\'s least documented — shaped by cattle-herding Nilotic traditions and the agricultural communities of the Nile\'s tributaries. Asida (sorghum porridge) and braised goat or beef are the foundations; fish from the White Nile supplements protein.',
    keyIngredients: ['sorghum (asida)', 'cow milk', 'goat', 'freshwater fish', 'peanuts', 'sesame', 'leafy greens', 'dried okra'],
    signatureDishes: [
      { name: 'Asida', description: 'Thick sorghum porridge cooked until very stiff and eaten by hand with a vegetable or meat stew — South Sudan\'s fundamental daily staple.' },
      { name: 'Ful Medames', description: 'Slow-cooked fava beans seasoned with cumin, lemon, and chili — shared with Sudan and Egypt, a breakfast staple along the entire Nile Valley.' },
      { name: 'Bamia', description: 'Okra stew with goat meat in a tomato sauce, eaten over asida — one of South Sudan\'s most widely cooked everyday dishes.' },
    ],
    images: [

    ],
    funFact: 'The Dinka people of South Sudan — the country\'s largest ethnic group — are one of the world\'s most devoted cattle-keeping cultures. Cattle are currency, prestige, and spiritual capital; Dinka men are often named after their favorite ox and a man\'s worth is measured in his herd.',
  },

  '262': {
    id: '262', name: 'Djibouti',
    description: 'Djiboutian cuisine is a distinctive blend of Somali, Afar, and Yemeni cooking traditions, shaped by the country\'s position at the mouth of the Red Sea. Skoudehkaris (spiced lamb and rice), fresh Red Sea fish, and anjero flatbread form the core of the Djiboutian table.',
    keyIngredients: ['lamb', 'basmati rice', 'Red Sea fish', 'anjero (fermented flatbread)', 'coconut milk', 'cardamom', 'fenugreek', 'dates'],
    signatureDishes: [
      { name: 'Skoudehkaris', description: 'Lamb slow-cooked with spiced rice, tomatoes, and peppers — Djibouti\'s national dish, a fragrant one-pot meal with Yemeni and Somali ancestry.' },
      { name: 'Fah-fah', description: 'A thin, peppery goat broth soup eaten for breakfast — Djibouti\'s most distinctive morning meal, believed to restore energy in the desert heat.' },
      { name: 'Lahoh', description: 'A spongy fermented pancake — shared with Yemen and Somalia, eaten with honey and butter for breakfast or alongside stews.' },
    ],
    images: [

    ],
    funFact: 'Djibouti sits at the Bab-el-Mandeb strait — the narrow waterway through which 30% of the world\'s oil supply passes. The country\'s strategic position has made it a military base for French, American, Chinese, and Japanese forces simultaneously — the only place in the world where all four nations have military bases.',
  },

